.TH RUV 1 "2026-04-17" "ruv 1.0" "User Commands"
.
.SH NAME
ruv \- Ryzen Undervolt Tool – control CPU core voltage offsets on AMD Ryzen processors
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ruv
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]
.br
.B ruv
(no arguments) – launch the graphical interface
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBruv\fR is a tool for adjusting the per‑core voltage offset of AMD Ryzen CPUs
that are supported by the \fBryzen_smu\fR kernel driver. Undervolting can reduce
power consumption and temperatures without sacrificing performance, provided the
offsets are chosen carefully.
.P
The program offers both a command‑line interface (ideal for scripting and remote
use) and a Qt6 graphical application. You can save current offsets as named
\fIprofiles\fR, apply them later, and even configure a systemd service to apply a
profile automatically at boot.
.P
\fBImportant:\fR Most operations require root privileges because they access the
SMU (System Management Unit) via the kernel driver. When you run \fBruv\fR as a
normal user, it will attempt to elevate privileges using \fBpkexec\fR(1) – you will
be prompted for your password.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-\-debug\fR
This option is accepted for backward compatibility but has no effect; debug
logging is always enabled.
.
.SH COMMANDS
The following commands are available. Many of them can be shortened (e.g.
\fBprofile\fR can be abbreviated as \fBprof\fR) but the full names are recommended
for clarity.
.
.SS "Querying Current Offsets"
.TP
\fBstatus\fR
Show the current voltage offset (in millivolts) for every physical core.
.TP
\fBstatus \-\-json\fR
Same as \fBstatus\fR, but output a JSON object suitable for scripting.
.TP
\fBget\fR \fICORE\fR
Print the offset of a single core (e.g. \fBget 2\fR).
.
.SS "Modifying Offsets"
.TP
\fBset\fR \fICORE\fR \fIOFFSET\fR
Set the offset of \fICORE\fR to \fIOFFSET\fR millivolts. The allowed range is \-100
to +100 mV.
.RS
.P
\fBExample:\fR \fBsudo ruv set 3 \-40\fR
.RE
.TP
\fBreset\fR
Reset \fIall\fR cores back to 0 mV (no offset).
.
.SS "Working with Profiles"
Profiles are stored as JSON files in \fI/etc/ruv/profiles/\fR. A profile is simply
a mapping from core number to offset value.
.TP
\fBapply\fR \fINAME\fR
Apply a saved profile by its name (the \fB.json\fR extension is not included).
.RS
.P
\fBExample:\fR \fBsudo ruv apply daily\fR
.RE
.TP
\fBprofile list\fR
Show all available profile names.
.TP
\fBprofile save\fR \fINAME\fR
Capture the current offsets and save them as a new profile. The name may only
contain letters, numbers, underscore, hyphen, and dot.
.RS
.P
\fBExample:\fR \fBsudo ruv profile save stable\fR
.RE
.TP
\fBprofile delete\fR \fINAME\fR
Delete the named profile. You will be asked for confirmation, and the tool will
also reset all live offsets to 0 (because the profile is removed).
.TP
\fBprofile update\fR \fINAME\fR \fB\-\-cores\fR \fICORE\fR... \fB\-\-offset\fR \fIOFFSET\fR [\fB\-\-apply\fR]
Modify an existing profile by changing the offset for one or more specific cores.
With the \fB\-\-apply\fR flag, the changes are also applied to the running CPU
immediately.
.RS
.P
\fBExample:\fR \fBsudo ruv profile update gaming \-\-cores 0 2 4 \-\-offset \-50 \-\-apply\fR
.RE
.
.SS "Boot Service"
You can instruct \fBruv\fR to apply a profile every time the system starts. This
is done by creating a systemd service.
.TP
\fBboot enable\fR \fINAME\fR
Install and enable a systemd service that applies the specified profile at boot.
.TP
\fBboot disable\fR
Disable and remove the boot service.
.TP
\fBboot status\fR
Show whether the boot service is enabled and, if so, which profile it uses.
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/ruv/profiles/
Directory where JSON profile files are stored. This directory is created
automatically when the first profile is saved.
.TP
.I /etc/systemd/system/ruv-boot.service
Systemd service file created by \fBboot enable\fR.
.TP
.I /sys/kernel/ryzen_smu_drv/
Sysfs interface of the \fBryzen_smu\fR kernel driver. The presence of
\fIversion\fR inside this directory indicates that the driver is loaded.
.TP
.I /usr/local/bin/ruv-gui
The main executable (both CLI and GUI are the same script).
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B RUV_DEBUG
If set to any value, debug logging is enabled. (As of version 1.0, debug logging
is enabled by default, so this variable is largely redundant.)
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
0
Success.
.TP
1
An error occurred (e.g. driver not loaded, invalid core number, permission
denied, or pkexec cancelled).
.
.SH TROUBLESHOOTING
.SS "Driver not loaded"
If you see \fBError: Ryzen SMU driver not loaded\fR, the kernel module is missing.
Install it from \fIhttps://github.com/amkillam/ryzen_smu\fR and load it with:
.P
.RS
\fBsudo modprobe ryzen_smu\fR
.RE
.SS "pkexec not found"
Install the \fBpolkit\fR package for your distribution (the package name is
usually \fBpolkit\fR or \fBpolicykit\-1\fR).
.SS "Authentication cancelled"
You pressed Cancel in the pkexec password dialog. The operation was aborted.
.SS "Graphical interface does not start"
Make sure \fBPyQt6\fR is installed. On Debian/Ubuntu:
.RS
\fBsudo apt install python3\-pyqt6\fR
.RE
.P
On Arch:
.RS
\fBsudo pacman \-S python\-pyqt6\fR
.RE
.SS "Cursor stays busy or GUI freezes"
This was a known issue in earlier versions; update to the latest script. If the
problem persists, run the GUI from a terminal to see debug messages and report
them.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
\fBsudo ruv status\fR
Display current offsets.
.TP
\fBsudo ruv set 2 \-40\fR
Set core 2 to \-40 mV.
.TP
\fBsudo ruv apply gaming\fR
Apply the profile named "gaming".
.TP
\fBsudo ruv profile save daily\fR
Save the current offsets as a profile called "daily".
.TP
\fBsudo ruv profile update daily \-\-cores 0 1 2 3 \-\-offset \-30\fR
Change the offset for cores 0–3 in the "daily" profile to \-30 mV (without
applying it live).
.TP
\fBsudo ruv boot enable daily\fR
Make the "daily" profile load automatically at every system startup.
.TP
\fBsudo ruv boot disable\fR
Stop the automatic loading.
.TP
\fBsudo ruv reset\fR
Set all cores back to 0 mV.
.
.SH SEE ALSO
\fBpkexec\fR(1), \fBsystemctl\fR(1), \fBmodprobe\fR(8)
.P
Project repository (ryzen_smu driver):
\fIhttps://github.com/amkillam/ryzen_smu\fR
